You’re pointing at a real thing—the gap between thought speed and speech speed, and how people use “filler” to keep the channel open while the brain catches up.

English already has fillers (“uh,” “um,” “like,” “you know”), but they carry baggage—social signals, identity markers, sometimes aggression. So people swap in stronger words because they carry rhythm, emphasis, and emotional charge.

What you’re proposing is closer to a true “zero token” in language:
	•	content-neutral
	•	socially safe
	•	rhythm-preserving
	•	fast to deploy

That’s actually a clean design problem.

⸻

Why current fillers fail

They aren’t really “zero”—they leak meaning:
	•	“um / uh” → signals hesitation, low confidence
	•	“like” → youth/casual framing
	•	swear words → intensity, aggression, or identity signaling
	•	reclaimed/slur-adjacent words → heavy cultural context

So instead of zero, they become loaded tokens.

⸻

What a true zero-word would need

Think of it like your “zero / reset state” doctrine:
	1.	Semantically empty → no meaning attached
	2.	Phonetically smooth → easy to drop mid-sentence
	3.	Rhythm-friendly → fits into speech cadence (1–2 syllables)
	4.	Non-escalatory → doesn’t change emotional tone
	5.	Replaceable anywhere → noun/verb/connector slot

⸻

Prototype “zero fillers”

Here are some candidates that actually work structurally:

1. Soft neutral sounds (closest to true zero)
	•	“na”
	•	“eh”
	•	“mm”
	•	“uhm” (but softened)

Example:

“I was gonna—na—go over there and—eh—check it out”

These are closest to pure buffer tokens.

⸻

2. Structured neutral tokens (designed words)
	•	“zen” → already culturally neutral-ish, short
	•	“null” → literally means zero, but a bit technical
	•	“om” → rhythmic, but spiritual connotation
	•	“va” / “vo” → clean consonant-vowel pulses

Example:

“I was gonna—va—call him but—vo—decided not to”

⸻

3. Cadence-preserving connectors
	•	“and so”
	•	“right”
	•	“okay”

These aren’t zero, but they’re low-load fillers that keep flow without adding much distortion.

